<p style="Standard" xid="179" props="bgcolor:#ffffff; margin-top:0.265cm; shading-foreground-color:#ffffff; margin-bottom:0cm; shading-pattern:1"><c></c></p>
<p style="normal" xid="180" props="margin-top:0.159cm; margin-left:0cm; shading-pattern:1; margin-bottom:0.159cm; text-indent:0.238cm; bgcolor:#ffffff; text-align:justify; margin-right:0cm; shading-foreground-color:#ffffff"><c props="font-style:italic; lang:en-US">Fate Core</c><c props="lang:en-US"> has a way of handling this, called mobs (see the </c><c props="font-style:italic; lang:en-US">“Creating the Opposition”</c><c props="lang:en-US"> section of the</c><c props="font-style:italic; lang:en-US">Running the Game</c><c props="lang:en-US"> chapter in </c><c props="font-style:italic; lang:en-US">Fate Core</c><c props="lang:en-US">). Feel free to use that option if you prefer. Note that it may lead to very strong mobs, unless you start with extremely weak mooks—if you want to give your PCs a serious challenge, that could be one way to do it.</c></p>
